{"cursor":"19990","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n\n'Continental drift' is the movement of the Earth's continents relative to each\nother by appearing to drift across the ocean bed. [http://pubs.usgs.gov/gip/dynamic/historical.html USGS:\nHistorical perspective on plate tectonics, last updated 19 September 2011]\nThe speculation that continents might have 'drifted' was first put forward by\nAbraham Ortelius in 1596. The concept was independently (and more fully)\ndeveloped by Alfred Wegener in 1912. The theory of continental drift was\nsuperseded by the theory of plate tectonics, which builds upon and better\nexplains why the continents move.\n","linknr":345,"url":"Continental_drift","recorded":1362372884,"links":69,"instances":["geology","scientist","engineer","fictitious"],"pdf":["http://www.geophysik.uni-frankfurt.de/~schmelin/skripte/Geodynn1-kap1-2-S1-S22-2004.pdf","http://www.geophysik.uni-frankfurt.de/~schmelin/skripte/Geodynn1-kap1-2-S1-S22-2004.pdf","http://www.lib.uchicago.edu/e/crerar/crerar-prize/2003%2004%20Brusatte.pdf","http://www.lib.uchicago.edu/e/crerar/crerar-prize/2003%2004%20Brusatte.pdf","http://web.archive.org/web/20120204234030/http://historyweb.ucsd.edu/oreskes/Papers/Continentaldrift2002.pdf","http://historyweb.ucsd.edu/oreskes/Papers/Continentaldrift2002.pdf","http://web.archive.org/web/20120204234030/http://historyweb.ucsd.edu/oreskes/Papers/Continentaldrift2002.pdf","http://epic.awi.de/Publications/Polarforsch2005_1_3.pdf","http://epic.awi.de/Publications/Polarforsch2005_1_3.pdf"],"categories":["Plate tectonics","Geological history of Earth"],"headings":["History","Evidence that continents 'drift'","Rejection of Wegener's theory, and subsequent vindication","Bibliography","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/69/Antonio_Snider-Pellegrini_Opening_of_the_Atlantic.jpg/300px-Antonio_Snider-Pellegrini_Opening_of_the_Atlantic.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/commo